Draft of argument to build an academic paper around: Popper's Epistemology as the Correct Foundation for Science Education

Feynman's apology — science education teaches content but not the scientific approach, and nothing has changed in 50 years.
The false equivalence problem — education curricula treat Popper as one voice among equals, the same mistake we don't make in physics education.
The Kuhn-Popper conflict dissolves — Kuhn mischaracterized Popper's position, and the apparent conflict is largely an artifact of that mischaracterization.
What Popper actually corrected — justificationism replaced by falsificationism, illustrated by the murder case.
Falsificationism requires systems thinking — you can't identify a causal mechanism without understanding the system's causal structure and finding the root cause.
Practical consequences at the individual level — oral examination reveals students can't explain causal mechanisms one level below the emergent property.
Practical consequences at the institutional level — the ulcer case shows entire medical subfields missing the root cause for decades.
The proposal — a dedicated Scientific Approach class taught every year alongside content classes.
The closing argument — getting epistemology right is the most fundamental lever for improving how the next generation of scientists, physicians, and thinkers reason.

In 1974, Richard Feynman stood before the graduating class at Caltech and apologized. He apologized on behalf of physics professors everywhere for never teaching students the scientific approach directly — for assuming they would absorb it by exposure to scientific work, the way islanders in the Pacific absorbed the forms of airport culture by watching planes land. Feynman was identifying a specific problem: university science professors who never explicitly learned the scientific approach, what Popper called epistemology1, themselves because it was assumed they would absorb it through doing science — and therefore cannot explicitly teach it. But there is a second and related problem that compounds the first. K-12 teachers and education researchers who went through formal education programs encounter epistemology directly — but in a form that actively obscures rather than clarifies the foundation science education should rest on. Those programs treat Popper's epistemology as one voice among several equally valid options, giving teachers not an absent epistemological foundation but a confused one. Problem one produces professors who teach content without epistemological grounding because they never had it explicitly themselves. Problem two produces teachers who teach content without epistemological grounding because they were taught that no single epistemological foundation is correct. Both problems produce the same outcome — students who never explicitly learn the scientific approach — but through different mechanisms requiring different solutions. Fifty years after Feynman's apology, neither problem has been adequately addressed. Both problems produce the same outcome — students who never explicitly learn the scientific approach — through different mechanisms. But both share the same broad recognition as their solution, and this paper treats them as one fundamental problem: that Popper's epistemology is not one voice among equals but the correct foundation for science education, and that treating it otherwise — whether through absence or through false equivalence — has specific and measurable consequences for how students learn to reason. The narrow solutions each problem requires in its specific context follow from that recognition and are addressed in subsequent work. 
The problem is visible in any survey of philosophy of education curricula. Epistemology sections routinely list Popper alongside Kuhn, Lakatos, Feyerabend, and others as if the question of how science works remains genuinely open; as if there is no better and worse answer, only different perspectives. This is a mistake physics education does not make. We do not teach Aristotelian physics alongside Einsteinian relativity as equally valid current options. We teach Aristotle as a historically important predecessor whose ideas were falsified and replaced by theories that have survived all attempts at refutation. Aristotelian mechanics was falsified and replaced by theories that have themselves since been falsified and replaced in turn. Some questions get settled in exactly this way, including epistemological ones, and treating settled questions as permanently open is not intellectual balance but intellectual paralysis. A teacher who has been taught that Popper is one interesting option among several has no clear epistemological framework when deciding how to teach scientific reasoning. They default to teaching content, because content is less controversial, while the epistemological process remains implicit and unexamined, exactly the situation Feynman was describing.
The apparent conflicts between Popper and his successors dissolve under scrutiny. Popper's epistemology has attracted extensive criticism from multiple directions, but the consistent pattern across that literature is that genuine contributions complement his core normative claim rather than defeat it, while apparent contradictions typically rest on mischaracterizations of his actual position.2 What that core normative claim actually says matters precisely here. Popper never claimed scientific progress was gradual — he prescribed a mechanism, bold conjecture exposed to rigorous criticism, not a pace or scale of change. And he never claimed science converges on a final certain truth — as Deutsch clarified, progress toward truth means movement from more flawed theories to less flawed theories, not arrival at a destination.3 Education curricula that treat the post-Popperian debate as leaving the normative question permanently open are inheriting mischaracterizations of Popper's actual position rather than resolving them — and leaving teachers without the epistemological foundation they need.
What teaching Popper correctly would change in practice begins with understanding what Popper actually corrected. Aristotle's justificationism, the idea dominant in Western thought for two thousand years that knowledge requires justification by other knowledge, produces an infinite regress with no honest resolution. Popper's replacement: knowledge requires not justification but falsifiability. A claim counts as knowledge not because it has been proven true by supporting evidence but because it has survived all attempts to show it false. The difference becomes vivid through a concrete example. Consider a murder trial. The prosecution presents a theory that the defendant committed the crime, supported by empirical evidence consistent with that theory. But the defense attorney doesn't need to prove the prosecution wrong directly; they only need to present an alternative theory that is also consistent with the same empirical evidence. That alone is sufficient to destroy the prosecution's case, because it demonstrates that the evidence was never as decisive as it appeared. Confirmation is meaningless. If a theory is consistent with all the empirical evidence, that does not imply that it's correct. A teacher who genuinely understands this teaches students to ask not "what evidence supports my theory?" but "what evidence would distinguish my theory from competing ones?" and “what alternative theory would also explain all the evidence?” They teach students that an explanation consistent with everything explains nothing. They teach students to trace causal mechanisms rather than accumulate correlations, because a correlation consistent with multiple causal theories does not help you select a theory from its rivals.
Popperian falsificationism leads naturally to a further requirement that is implicit in his framework even though he didn't use this vocabulary explicitly. To falsify a causal claim you must first identify what causal claim you are actually making — and that requires understanding how the parts of the system relate to each other causally. A correlation between two phenomena is consistent with multiple competing causal theories and therefore falsifies none of them. The correct question is not "does this observation fit my theory?" but "what is the causal mechanism connecting these parts of the system, and at what level does the root cause operate?" This is systems thinking — tracing causal relationships between the parts of a system to identify the constraint generating the problem at its deepest level rather than stopping at a surface correlation or a symptom. Goldratt made this vocabulary explicit, but the requirement is already implicit in Popper. You cannot do falsificationism correctly without doing systems thinking, because falsificationism requires identifying the causal mechanism you are actually testing, and identifying that mechanism requires understanding the system's causal structure at the level where the root cause operates.
The practical consequences are visible in oral examination of premed students using Socratic questioning. The most common reasoning failure encountered is not factual ignorance — students can reproduce correct answers. It is the inability to explain the causal mechanism one level below the emergent property being described. Asked why warm air rises, a student will say "because hot air is less dense." Asked why hot air is less dense, the same student will often stop — not because they lack the knowledge to go further, but because they have never been taught that an explanation requires identifying the mechanism, not just restating the phenomenon at a slightly more abstract level. This is a direct consequence of science education that teaches conclusions without teaching the epistemological standard that distinguishes a genuine explanation from a redescription. A student who had been explicitly taught Popper's framework — that an explanation must identify a falsifiable causal mechanism — would know that their answer was incomplete and would know what completing it requires. The same failure appears in how students handle correlation and causation. They know the phrase as a slogan. They do not reliably apply it as a reasoning tool, because they have never been taught the Popperian reason it matters — a correlation without a causal mechanism is an unfalsified just-so story, consistent with multiple competing theories and therefore not evidence for any one of them.
When students trained without explicit epistemological grounding become physicians, the same reasoning failures operate at an institutional scale with serious consequences. The organization of medicine into narrow specialties — gastroenterology, neurology, cardiology, endocrinology — is a structural systems thinking failure embedded in the profession itself. Each specialist looks at their part of the system without asking what the root cause is at the level of the whole patient. A gastroenterologist treats gut symptoms, a neurologist treats cognitive symptoms, an endocrinologist treats hormonal symptoms — each within their own theoretical framework, each limited to the hypotheses their specialty generates, none necessarily asking what constraint is operating at the level of the whole biological system and producing manifestations across multiple domains simultaneously. The patient is fragmented into organs that are treated independently when the root cause may be operating at the interface between what two specialists consider their separate territories. Medicine's own internal correction of this failure is revealing — when the silo structure produces bad enough outcomes, a bridging specialty gets created. Interventional neurology emerged because the boundary between neurology and vascular medicine was producing worse stroke outcomes than a specialty that explicitly traced root causes across that boundary. Neuropsychiatry emerged because the boundary between neurology and psychiatry was preventing the identification of neurological root causes of psychiatric symptoms. Each bridging specialty is medicine recognizing, after the fact, that the institutional structure was artificially separating things that are causally connected in the actual biological system. The physicians exposing these failures are doing exactly what Popperian training should produce — tracing causal relationships across the whole system, refusing to treat symptoms while ignoring what generates them, and proposing bolder hypotheses about root causes that the existing institutional framework wasn't generating. Their relative rarity is the problem. Their existence is the proof that systems thinking in medicine produces better outcomes when it is finally applied.
The proposal that follows from this analysis is specific and implementable. Every university major has a first required course in its primary discipline. That course should open with two weeks of explicit Scientific Approach instruction — falsificationism, systems thinking, root cause analysis, causal mechanisms versus correlations — taught using examples from that specific discipline. A biology major encounters the framework through biology examples. A chemistry major encounters it through chemistry examples. A physics major encounters it through physics examples. This ensures the framework is immediately concrete and immediately applicable rather than abstract and disconnected from the student's actual work. Every subsequent course assumes that foundation without re-teaching it — the same way statistics is taught once in thermodynamics and then assumed in every course that follows. Then in the final year of the degree, a standalone capstone course returns to the Scientific Approach at a more sophisticated level — not re-teaching the basics but examining the framework explicitly in light of the deep domain knowledge the student has accumulated across four years, connecting their specific disciplinary experience to the broader epistemological principles, and pushing into more advanced territory that requires the maturity and knowledge the student now possesses. The professor delivering the introductory two weeks doesn't need to be a philosopher of science — they need to understand the Scientific Approach deeply enough to make it explicit in their own domain, using their own discipline's examples. A full account of what that training requires, and what the Scientific Approach as a complete teachable framework consists of, is beyond the scope of this paper and is the necessary subject of subsequent work.
The epistemological confusion this paper identifies is not a minor academic oversight — it has consequences that reach from philosophy seminars all the way into the clinic, where physicians trained without explicit epistemological grounding make reasoning errors that cost patients their lives. A teacher who has been taught that Popper is one voice among equals cannot confidently teach Popperian reasoning as the correct foundation for scientific thinking. A professor who doesn't clearly understand the difference between falsificationism and justificationism cannot make that difference explicit in the first two weeks of their introductory course. Resolving that confusion requires education curricula to make a distinction they currently avoid — between epistemological questions that remain genuinely open and those that have been falsified and replaced by better frameworks. Popper's core insights belong in the second category. Treating them as belonging in the first has real costs, measured not in philosophical imprecision but in patient outcomes, in students who cannot distinguish explanation from redescription, and in entire subfields of science that spend decades accumulating confirming evidence for theories whose root causes they never correctly identified. Getting this right is not an academic housekeeping matter. It is the most fundamental lever available for improving how the next generation of scientists, physicians, and thinkers actually reason — and it begins with taking seriously what Feynman was asking for fifty years ago.
Footnotes:
The equation between epistemology and the scientific approach is not an arbitrary terminological choice. Popper's original German title for what English speakers know as The Logic of Scientific Discovery was Logik der Forschung: Zur Erkenntnistheorie der modernen Naturwissenschaft — literally "Logic of Research: On the Epistemology of Modern Natural Science." Popper himself was treating epistemology and the scientific approach as the same inquiry. Furthermore, Popper explicitly held that rationality is not restricted to empirical or scientific theories but is a special case of the general method of criticism — finding and eliminating contradictions in knowledge — applicable to metaphysical ideas, moral values, and all domains of human inquiry. This paper follows Popper's own usage: epistemology, the scientific approach, and reason, properly understood, are the same fundamental activity applied to different domains. A full account of this equation and its implications is developed in subsequent work.
The most prominent example is Kuhn's paradigm shift model, often presented as contradicting Popper's falsificationism. Kuhn raised several objections. First, he argued that scientists spend most of their time in "normal science" — solving puzzles within an established paradigm — rather than constantly trying to falsify fundamental theories. This is a valid historical observation but it operates at the descriptive level, not the normative one. Popper was prescribing what scientists should do to generate knowledge, not describing what they always do in practice. The gap between the two is real but it doesn't defeat Popper's normative claim — it identifies a systematic human tendency to resist falsification that Popper's framework correctly diagnoses as a problem. Second, Kuhn argued that some dogmatic commitment to a paradigm is productive — it allows scientists to go deep rather than constantly questioning foundations. This is the most genuinely interesting of Kuhn's observations. But provisional practical commitment to a framework for purposes of productive inquiry is different from treating that framework as unfalsifiable in principle. A scientist can work within a paradigm while remaining open to its falsification — that is pragmatic efficiency, not dogmatism, and it is fully compatible with Popperian epistemology. Third, Kuhn argued that scientists don't immediately abandon theories when contradictory evidence appears, which he presented as contradicting Popper's logic. But Popper never required immediate theory abandonment upon encountering a single anomaly — he argued that persistence in the face of overwhelming falsifying evidence, and deliberate insulation of a theory from genuine attempts at refutation, are what constitute irrational dogmatism. A single anomaly is not automatically a falsification. Fourth, Kuhn argued that different paradigms are incommensurable — so different that rational comparison between them is impossible. The historical evidence contradicts this directly. Einstein did not discard Newton but revealed its boundary conditions and incorporated it as a special case, which is precisely commensurable comparison — we can identify exactly where Newton's predictions match Einstein's and where they diverge. As Deutsch clarified, Popper's progress toward truth means from more flawed to less flawed theory, not convergence on a final destination, which Kuhn's own position does not actually contradict. The consistent pattern across Kuhn's objections is that they either operate at the descriptive level while Popper's claim is normative, or they rest on mischaracterizations of Popper's actual position. Popper's framework has also been refined and corrected by Popperians themselves — demonstrating that the tradition is self-correcting in exactly the way Popper's epistemology predicts it should be. A comprehensive defense of Popper's epistemology against the full range of objections in the post-Popperian literature is beyond the scope of this paper and unnecessary — that work has already been done thoroughly by Popper himself and by later Popperians. Readers seeking that defense are directed to Popper's The Logic of Scientific Discovery and Conjectures and Refutations, and to Deutsch's The Fabric of Reality and The Beginning of Infinity.
Deutsch develops this clarification of Popper's notion of progress toward truth in The Beginning of Infinity (2011). The key point is that "closer to the truth" does not mean convergence on a final certain truth — which would reintroduce justificationism through the back door — but rather movement from theories with more flaws to theories with fewer flaws, through the mechanism of conjecture and criticism. Each theory that survives rigorous attempts at refutation is less wrong than the one it replaced, without being final or certain. This is a crucial clarification because the most common misreading of Popper — including Kuhn's — attributes to him a naive convergence on final truth that he never held. Deutsch's formulation makes Popper's actual position precise and immune to that misreading. Readers are directed to The Beginning of Infinity for the full development of this and related clarifications of Popperian epistemology.




